name: dodecanal
Reason: The aldehyde functional group in dodecanal typically lowers the melting point compared to a similar length alkane because of its polar nature, which can disrupt the orderly packing of molecules; however, the long carbon chain in dodecanal provides van der Waals forces that significantly contribute to the melting point. Basic unit hexane has a melting point of -95°C. Each additional -CH2- group adds about +5°C due to increased van der Waals forces. We have 12 carbons in dodecanal versus 6 in hexane, which adds (12-6)*5 = 30°C. The aldehyde group tends to lower the melting point by around -20°C compared to a methyl end group due to the different in packing efficiency and polarity.

Each additional -CH2- group in a saturated hydrocarbon chain typically contributes approximately +5°C to the melting point. Dodecanal has a total of 12 carbons, meaning there are six additional -CH2- groups compared to hexane, which would theoretically increase the melting point by 6*5 = +30°C. However, the aldehyde group at the end of the chain impacts the melting point as well, expected to lower it; traditionally, an aldehyde group can reduce the melting point by around -15°C compared to a terminal methyl group. This is due to the polar nature of the aldehyde group and the resulting less efficient packing.
